                    <span>This amazing business success story reads like a fast-paced novel.  You don't have to know anything about the airline industry to find BLUE STREAK fascinating.  I couldn't put it down once I began. Now I feel I have an inside look at something I knew virtually nothing about before.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Compulsively readable</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>0</span>
                      /
                      <span>0</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-01-10</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>I picked "Blue Streak" up with the idea of leafing through it, and didn't put it down until I reached the last page. Peterson's account is intelligent, well-researched, and in parts, almost unbelievable -- like most great business stories, the personalities that steered Jet Blue to the stars are larger than life. Peterson clearly knows the industry inside out -- her "set pieces" on the founders of Southwest and Virgin are worth the price of admission on their own. My only quibble is that I wished she'd gone deeper into a couple of areas, e.g. Neeleman's personal life. But all in all, a terrific read from an exceptional journalist.</span>
                  
              
